# Namespaces:
ðŸ‘‰ is a logical partition inside a cluster that lets you organize and isolate resources. Think of it like folders inside a computer.
ðŸ‘‰ each namespace holds its own pods, services, deployments, etc.
ðŸ‘‰ One Kubernetes cluster â†’ multiple namespaces â†’ separated environments.

# Why namespaces are used:
âœ… Environment separation (dev / test / prod)
âœ… Multi-team resource isolation
âœ… Access control (RBAC per namespace)
âœ… Resource quotas & limits
âœ… Cleaner organization

# Kubernetes comes with a few built-in namespaces:
| Namespace           | Purpose                                             |
| ------------------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| **default**         | Where resources go if you donâ€™t specify a namespace |
| **kube-system**     | System components (DNS, scheduler, controller)      |
| **kube-public**     | Public readable resources                           |
| **kube-node-lease** | Node heartbeat tracking                             |

# Basic namespace commands 
ðŸ‘‰ Create namespace :- kubectl create namespace dev
ðŸ‘‰ List namespaces :- kubectl get namespaces
ðŸ‘‰ Run pod inside namespace :- kubectl run nginx --image=nginx -n dev
ðŸ‘‰ View resources in namespace :- kubectl get pods -n dev            ($kubectl get pods command look pods in default namesapce).
ðŸ‘‰ List all pods in ps output format with more information in namespace :- kubectl get pods -o wide -n dev
ðŸ‘‰ Print a detailed description of pods in namespace :- kubectl describe pods -n dev
ðŸ‘‰ List all pods existing in all namespaces :- kubectl get pods --all-namespaces
ðŸ‘‰ Delete resources in namespace :- kubectl delete <resource_type> <resource_name> -n <namespace>
  Example :- if i want to delete pod of dev namespace by $kubectl delete pod webserver -n dev. 
    


Note :- if you dont specify namespace when creating any resource it will create in default namespace.
